<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia</i> <i>farinosa</i> and <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i> are co-dominant
and equally conspicuous in the shrub canopy with <i>Agave</i> <i>deserti</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>hymenelytra</i>, <i>Bebbia</i> <i>juncea</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>bigelovii</i>, <i>Dasyochloa</i> <i>pulchella</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>inflatum</i>, <i>Fagonia</i> <i>laevis</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Krameria</i> <i>grayi</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>basilaris</i> and <i>Stephanomeria</i> <i>pauciflora</i>. Emergent trees or tall shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Fouquieria</i> <i>splendens</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is open to intermittent, and two tiered. Herbaceous layer is open with seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li>Both <i>Encelia farinosa</i> and <i>Larrea tridentata</i> > 1%
absolute cover in the shrub canopy; no other woody
species can greatly exceed their cover. <i>Ambrosia
dumosa, Agave deserti, Opuntia</i> spp., and emergent
<i>Fouquieria splendens</i> may be present with < 5% absolute cover
(Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
		
		<li>Both <i>Encelia farinosa</i> and <i>Larrea tridentata</i> > 1% absolute cover in the shrub canopy. <i>Ambrosia dumosa</i> may be present (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Larrea tridentata</i> generally ≥ 1% and evenly distributed across the stand. <i>Encelia farinosa</i> ≥ 1% cover, may have higher cover than <i>Larrea tridentata. Ambrosia dumosa</i> may be present but at generally lower cover than <i>Encelia farinosa</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Small washes, rills, alluvial fans, bajadas, colluvium on upland slopes. Soils are well drained, rocky, may have desert pavement surfaces, and are often derived from granitic or volcanic rock.  </div>
</div>

        
