<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Larrea tridentata </i>is a very long-lived shrub (10,000+ years as a clone), and under good conditions it develops a deep and widely spreading root system. The plant survives in deep, sandy soils or in rocky areas more effectively than other shrubs because of its spreading root system (Marshall 1995b). Further, <i>L. tridentata </i>is extremely resistant to high temperatures and low tissue water potential. Its resinous leaves are ideally anti-transpiring because they diminish transpiration more than assimilation (Meinzer et al. 1990). It is thereby successfully dominating landscapes throughout most of the hot deserts in California. Mature plants may be allelopathic to their own seedlings, encouraging an open community structure. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Encelia farinosa </i>is a short-lived sub-shrub that lives to 30 years in age. It leafs outs and flowers whenever moisture is available. It reproduces by seed and weakly sprouts from damaged stems. It is allelopathic to several winter annual species. It is fire sensitive, as it is intolerant of heat from fire, with sprouting weak or non-existent. However, it can quickly re-colonize areas from off-site seed sources (Tesky 1993b), and seedlings rapidly colonize roadsides and other disturbed areas. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is found on hotter, rockier, and often steeper environments than the <i>Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa </i>alliance and tends to be less diverse with a lower proportion of annual herbs in rainy years. It is not found on sandy or clay-rich soils. Widespread in the southern and central Mojave Desert and throughout much of the Sonoran and Colorado deserts, this alliance represents a drought-tolerant expression of the American desert scrub dominated by <i>L. tridentata</i>. Despite the colonizing properties of <i>E. farinosa, </i>the alliance is generally stable. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
