    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-b, Cd). Stands commonly occur on granitic slopes below 700 m, including the Coachella Valley (Evens and Hartman 2007). A study for Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) concluded that areas mapped as <i>Encelia farinosa</i> series are more accurately considered part of this alliance. This alliance includes areas with a high cacti diversity. Brown and Minnich (1986) studied the fire history in the Palm Springs area, suggesting that much area had been converted to <i>E. farinosa</i> stands as a result of fire.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ab-f, Ah-p). Stands occur in all but the northernmost and westernmost subsections. Stands exist at Twentynine Palms Marine Corps Base (Minnich et al. 1993) and generally for the central and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004). The alliance may occupy limestone and other calcareous mountains such as in the Nopah Range and Silurian Hills, as well as granitics and volcanics. The northernmost stands occur on volcanics near Panamint Springs.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands occur commonly on slopes and well-drained upper bajadas and alluvial fans throughout the section (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fe-f). Stands occur in the southern subsections on steep slopes of the Argus and Panamint mountains.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This is another alliance where non-native annual grass invasion and human-related fires have coincided in threatening its structure and diversity. Fires should be excluded at all times of the year and core areas should be identified where grass cover is low and stands are defensible. Unlike the <i>Larrea tridentata</i>-<i>Ambrosia dumosa </i>alliance, the rocky steep nature of many of the stands preclude the establishment of a dense cover of <i>Bromus rubens, </i>so resistance to fire and invasion may be high. <i>Brassica tournefortii </i>is a new non-native that is successfully invading stands of this alliance. </div>
</div>

    

    

